etymologies: late Middle English: from late Latin incorporat- ‘embodied’, from the verb incorporare, from in- ‘into’ + Latin corporare ‘form into a body’ (from corpus, corpor- ‘body’)

definitions: take in or contain (something) as part of a whole; include

examples.text: he has incorporated in his proposals a number of measures
some schemes incorporated all these variations

definitions: combine (ingredients) into one substance

examples.text: add the cheeses and butter and process briefly to incorporate them

definitions: constitute (a company, city, or other organization) as a legal corporation

examples.text: limited liability companies could only be incorporated under the 1930 Act

definitions: having a bodily form; embodied

examples.text: through an incorporate resilience, slighted confidence restores itself

etymologies: late Middle English: from Latin irrationalis, from in- ‘not’ + rationalis (see rational)

definitions: not logical or reasonable

examples.text: irrational feelings of hostility

definitions: not endowed with the power of reason.
shortDefinitions: not endowed with power of reason

definitions: (of a number, quantity, or expression) not expressible as a ratio of two integers, and having an infinite and non-recurring expansion when expressed as a decimal. Examples of irrational numbers are the number π and the square root of 2.
shortDefinitions: (of number, quantity, or expression) not expressible as ratio of two integers

definitions: an irrational number or quantity; a surd.
excessively excited

examples.text: they were forced to hide from overexcited fans who threatened to riot

etymologies: late 16th century: via Latin from Greek exōtikos ‘foreign’, from exō ‘outside’

definitions: originating in or characteristic of a distant foreign country

examples.text: exotic birds
they loved to visit exotic places

shortDefinitions: from or characteristic of foreign country

definitions: attractive or striking because colourful or out of the ordinary

examples.text: youths with exotic haircuts
there was a touch of the exotic in her appearance

definitions: (especially of metals or fuels) of a kind not ordinarily encountered; specially produced

examples.text: exotic chemicals such as oil hydrocarbons

definitions: an exotic plant or animal

examples.text: he planted exotics in the sheltered garden

definitions: a broker who buys and sells securities on a stock exchange on behalf of clients.
shortDefinitions: broker who buys and sells securities on stock exchange on behalf of clients

definitions: interpret (something or someone) wrongly

examples.text: I think you're misinterpreting the situation
Soanes claimed his remarks had been misinterpreted

definitions: out of date; obsolete

examples.text: outdated equipment

definitions: a person who supervises a person or an activity.
shortDefinitions: person who supervises person or activity

definitions: a person who directs and oversees the work of a postgraduate research student.
shortDefinitions: person who directs and oversees work of postgraduate research student

etymologies: mid 17th century (earlier (late Middle English) as fluctuation): from Latin fluctuat- ‘undulated’, from the verb fluctuare, from fluctus ‘flow, current, wave’, from fluere ‘to flow’

definitions: rise and fall irregularly in number or amount

examples.text: trade with other countries tends to fluctuate from year to year

shortDefinitions: rise and fall irregularly in number or amount

definitions: to an extent which is clearly noticeable; significantly

examples.text: new diagnoses have increased markedly since 1998
this advice is markedly different to that last year

shortDefinitions: to extent which is clearly noticeable

definitions: not producing any significant or desired effect

examples.text: the legal sanctions against oil spills are virtually ineffective
a weak and ineffective leader

shortDefinitions: not producing any significant or desired effect

etymologies: Old English blāc ‘shining, white’, or in later use from synonymous Old Norse bleikr; ultimately of Germanic origin and related to bleach

definitions: (of an area of land) lacking vegetation and exposed to the elements

examples.text: a bleak and barren moor

definitions: (of a building or room) charmless and inhospitable; dreary

examples.text: he looked round the bleak little room in despair

definitions: (of the weather) cold and miserable

examples.text: a bleak midwinter's day

definitions: (of a situation) not hopeful or encouraging; unlikely to have a favourable outcome

examples.text: he paints a bleak picture of a company that has lost its way
the future looks bleak

definitions: (of a person's expression) cold and forbidding

examples.text: his mouth was set and his eyes were bleak

etymologies: late 15th century: from Old Norse bleikja

definitions: a small silvery shoaling fish of the carp family, found in Eurasian rivers.

notes.text: Genera Alburnus and Chalcalburnus, family Cyprinidae: several species, in particular A. alburnus

shortDefinitions: small silvery shoaling fish of carp family

etymologies: mid 17th century: from late Latin ultimatus, past participle of ultimare ‘come to an end’

definitions: being or happening at the end of a process; final

examples.text: their ultimate aim was to force his resignation

shortDefinitions: being or happening at end of process

definitions: basic or fundamental

examples.text: the ultimate constituents of anything that exists are atoms

definitions: denoting the maximum possible strength or resistance beyond which an object breaks.
shortDefinitions: denoting maximum possible strength or resistance beyond which object breaks

definitions: being the best or most extreme example of its kind

examples.text: the ultimate accolade

shortDefinitions: being best or most extreme example of its kind

definitions: the best achievable or imaginable of its kind

examples.text: the ultimate in decorative luxury

shortDefinitions: best achievable or imaginable of its kind

definitions: a final or fundamental fact or principle.
shortDefinitions: final or fundamental fact or principle

etymologies: Old English fōstrian ‘feed, nourish’, from fōster‘food, nourishment’, of Germanic origin; related to food. The sense ‘bring up another's (originally also one's own) child’ dates from Middle English. See also foster-

definitions: encourage the development of (something, especially something desirable)

examples.text: the teacher's task is to foster learning

definitions: develop (a feeling or idea) in oneself

examples.text: appropriate praise helps a child foster a sense of self-worth

shortDefinitions: develop feeling or idea in oneself

definitions: bring up (a child that is not one's own by birth)

examples.text: a person who would foster Holly was found

definitions: (of a parent or authority) assign (a child) to be brought up by someone other than its parents

examples.text: when fostering out a child, placement workers will be looking for a home similar to their own

etymologies: late Middle English: from Anglo-Norman French receite, from medieval Latin recepta ‘received’, feminine past participle of Latin recipere. The -p- was inserted in imitation of the Latin spelling

definitions: the action of receiving something or the fact of its being received

examples.text: I would be grateful if you would acknowledge receipt of this letter
families in receipt of supplementary benefit

shortDefinitions: action of receiving something or fact of its being received

definitions: a written or printed statement acknowledging that something has been paid for or that goods have been received

examples.text: always make sure you get a receipt

shortDefinitions: written or printed statement acknowledging that something has been paid for or that goods have been received

definitions: an amount of money received during a particular period by an organization or business

examples.text: box office receipts

shortDefinitions: amount of money received during particular period

definitions: proof or evidence of something

examples.text: she had the receipts, and showed Rachel texts he had sent her

definitions: a recipe

examples.text: she spent hours in the kitchen, trying all sorts of receipts

definitions: mark (a bill) as paid

examples.text: one copy can be receipted and returned to you
the receipted hotel bill
